T1  - Public debt sustainability and endogenous seigniorage in Brazil: time-series evidence from 1947–1992
AU  - Issler, João Victor
AU  - Lima, Luiz Renato
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 62
IS  - 1
SP  - 131
EP  - 147
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3878(00)00078-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030438780000078X
KW  - Government-debt sustainability
KW  - Unit-root and co-integration tests
AB  - In this paper, we investigate three central issues in public finance. First, was the path of public debt sustainable during 1947–1992? Second, how has the government balanced the budget after shocks to either revenues or expenditures were observed? Third, are expenditures exogenous? The results show that (i) debt is sustainable in econometric tests, with the budget being balanced almost entirely through changes in taxes, regardless of the cause of the initial imbalance. Expenditures are weakly exogenous; (ii) the behavior of a “rational” Brazilian consumer may be consistent with Ricardian Equivalence; (iii) seigniorage revenues are critical in restoring intertemporal budget equilibrium.
